Dear Representative Ocasio-Cortez,

*Archive note: This piece was written for the public record on an active oversight moment: Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez placing two jars of brown well water on a congressional witness table on May 20, 2026, while demanding an EPA investigation into Meta's Stanton Springs campus in Morgan County, Georgia. It is archived here as part of the Liana Banyan civic accountability series, alongside the Sanders-AOC AI Data Center Moratorium Act and the infrastructure-economics argument that the cooperative model answers the same question the moratorium raises: who has the power to decide how AI gets built and who pays for it.*

[HOOK — Founder lede. Suggested anchor: the Ashburn imagery is yours. The aerial photo of the AWS data center in Loudoun County. The hum the residents hear at 3 a.m. The water table draw. The transmission lines crossing land that used to be horse country. Connect to the Representative's record on environmental justice and on the political-economy framing of infrastructure as a public good versus a corporate extraction.]

I'm writing because on May 20, 2026, you brought two mason jars of brown well water from the tap of Beverly Morris, a resident of Mansfield in Morgan County, Georgia, to a hearing of the House Committee on Energy and Commerce. You set those jars on the table in front of EPA Assistant Administrator for Water Jessica Kramer and demanded a federal investigation into whether Meta's Stanton Springs data center had contaminated the local water supply. Your question elicited from Administrator Kramer the on-record commitment: "As soon as I get back into my office, I will be looking into exactly what you just talked about." Meta disputes the causal link, but the image is on the record: a Member of Congress, two jars of discolored water, and a federal agency now engaged. That is not a fringe fight. That is the grid-impact argument in its most visceral form.

Six states are considering similar legislation. In March, you and Senator Sanders introduced the AI Data Center Moratorium Act, which would halt construction of facilities above 20 megawatts until strong national safeguards exist. I am not writing to ask you to hold that line or abandon it. I am writing because there is a third option that the current Congressional debate has not yet put on the table, and it changes the terms of the fight.

President Trump has threatened to sue any state that "regulates AI growth." The federalism fight is being framed as AI growth versus state sovereignty.

It is not. It is one specific architecture's growth versus state sovereignty. The distinction matters more than the current debate has noticed.

The data centers being built in Ashburn, the ones proposed in Maine and Minnesota and Michigan, all run the same architectural pattern: a frontier-tier large language model hosted in a mega-data-center, drawing megawatts of power and millions of gallons of cooling water, answering each query at roughly the cost of a frontier-model API call. That pattern was selected by a small number of corporate decisions over the last five years. It is not a property of AI as a category. It is one choice about how to deliver AI capability.

A different choice produces a different fight. We finished a controlled cross-architecture benchmark this morning: 1,170 graded responses across sixteen vendor-native and Cathedral-routed conditions. The headline finding: **same indexed-retrieval substrate, six different language models behind it, the answers cluster within three points of each other across the six models, at a 180-times cost spread.** The model doesn't matter; the index does. The cheapest small-model-plus-substrate condition delivers equivalent accuracy to the most expensive frontier-LLM-plus-injection condition for **76 times less compute spend per correct answer** (industry-term compute spend; same 200 questions; same architecture). At full Cathedral coverage, the projected per-correct-answer cost on the cheapest small-model configuration is **on the order of one-third of a cent**.

A data center running this substrate-amplified architecture draws roughly five-to-twenty times less power per useful answer than the Ashburn-class facilities. There is no obvious technical reason the next wave of data center buildouts has to choose the Ashburn architecture over the substrate-amplified one. The reason is not technical. It is corporate path-dependence and a regulatory-capture story that I think you will recognize.

[HOOK — Founder voice. Suggested anchor: the regulatory-capture frame is your lane. The major labs are not building substrate-amplified architectures because their business model depends on selling frontier-tier API calls. The architectural choice is downstream of vendor lock-in. Connect to the Cooperative Defensive Patent Pledge -- the IP frame Liana Banyan operates under, which explicitly licenses these patents for cooperative use. The architecture is open. The licensing is cooperative. There is no Amazon-style enclosure here.]

The reason I'm writing to you specifically is that the federalism fight is being argued on the wrong terrain. The current shape -- Trump threatens to sue states that block data centers, states feel cornered, the moratorium fight gets reframed as "anti-AI" -- is a fight engineered by the architecture's beneficiaries to make any state-level pushback look like Luddism. It isn't. State legislators in Maine, New York, Minnesota, and Michigan are responding to the documented externalities of one specific architecture: power draw, water consumption, home energy bill increases, transmission load. They are not anti-AI. They are pro-grid.

Architectural standards reframe this fight. If the next wave of data center proposals adopts the substrate-amplified pattern, there is nothing left to ban. The grid impact, the water impact, the cost-of-living impact on residents: these are artifacts of the Ashburn architecture, not properties of AI. The moratorium debate evaporates. The federalism fight evaporates. President Trump's threat to sue states becomes a fight about a problem that no longer exists.

[HOOK — Founder voice. Connect to the Oregon AI slop case ($109,700 fine, 1,300+ documented hallucination cases in courts). Same pattern: the slop is an architectural artifact (raw frontier LLM without provenance grounding), not a property of AI. Substrate-grounded architectures cannot generate citations they cannot resolve. The Authoritative-Answer-AI demonstration -- it's OK for AI to say "I don't know" -- is the legal-system version of the same Maine argument.]

I am asking for one specific thing: a Congressional working group on substrate-grounded AI infrastructure standards, before the federalism fight forces a worse outcome. **Every empirical claim above is reproducible by any third party** — we publish the dataset, the harness, and the benchmark results, and any state government, university, or independent auditor can replicate the run on their own hardware in roughly an hour at the smallest dataset size. We have also released a working Chrome extension that puts cooperative-substrate AI memory at every search bar for any member who wants to try the architecture in production for themselves; the curation flow is structured so that the member's own data stays on the member's own machine by default. The patents are licensed cooperatively. We will publish, demonstrate, and host the architecture at any state-government scale. We are not asking Congress to legislate the architecture. We are asking Congress to *put it on the table* so that the state-level fights have a third option to consider.

[HOOK — Founder closing. Suggested anchor: connect to the Representative's record on public-infrastructure-as-public-good. Or: the Founder's family register — eight kids, the people whose neighborhoods get the substations and the cooling-water-draw and the noise. Or: the architectural philosophy. We didn't train our Husky, Inuka, not to bark; we taught him to speak on command. The choice is not stifle versus unleash. The choice is direct.]

The fight in Maine is winnable on terms that do not require choosing between mill town jobs and grid stability — *if* a substrate-amplified architecture is on the table as a third option. The fight against the Trump-administration threat to sue states is winnable on terms that do not require accepting the Ashburn architecture as the only AI architecture. Both fights need an architectural alternative to be visible at the federal level. That is what I am asking you to help make visible.

Yours,

Jonathan Jones
Founder, Liana Banyan Corporation
[contact]

